"Steve" == Steve Gardner <gardner@aurora.cc.monash.edu.au> writes:

Steve> What reason is there for denying that a negative balance in the
Steve> Bank simply means that the Chancellor should mint that many
Steve> units of Currency in order to cancel the debt? Sure, it's
Steve> technical, but it's not absurd.

You're creating an obligation out of thin cloth.  I'd say that you
need support in the Rules to accomodate that interpretation, and that
supoprt does not exist.

I have yet to be presented with a reasonable model of absolute
possession in which negative possessed quantities has a reasonable
interpretation.  The obvious one, that the negative quantity
represents a debt, fails because without a debtor there cannot be a
debt, and there is no entity capable of acting in the role of debtor.
The other arguments I have seen rely solely on Rule 116 for support,
but the permissibility of a thing does not ensure its possibility.
Given the lack of a convincing reason why it should be possible for an
entity--especially the Bank--to possess a negative quantity of a
Currency, and the obvious problems with doing so, I must refuse to
recognize the attempts to attribute the possession of negative
quantities to the Bank as illogical and impossible.

